2025-02-01 14:48:23: shouldPasteResources: Pasted text: 1 round = battle phase + shop phase

Battle phase Ui: 

player hp (starting 60)
Player gold (starting 5)
Player Items and combos

Enemy hp
Enemy gold
Enemy items and combos 
Enemy dice pool

Dice pool to roll your dice
And a dedicated button: Reroll selected dice/skip -> lock in dice. 

Dice are scored from left to right for their base value, then if they are in a combo, multiply their value accordingly. Larger combos should trigger first.

Shop phase:

Player, enemy gold, hp, inventory
Combo slot (unlocks new combo for player)
Item slot (passive effects like shields +1)
Dice mod slot (replace one face on a die with another)

After each battle a screen that shows damage dealt, recieved, gold gained for both. Gold is round gained gold + income

Then enter shop. The player who had to reroll first goes first in the shop phase. Each player can buy up to one item. Instead of buyinf from the shop, the player can buy basic combos (first gained for free, second 5g, third 10g) 
The shop can be rerolled once per player for 3g. 

Basic combos (×2 multiplier): sword+horse, sword+shield, shield+horse

When player reaches 0 hp, they lose.

2025-02-02 20:01:31: shouldPasteResources: Pasted text: one approach you can take in C++ where you “attach” a set of conditions or an exact number sequence to each combo and then loop over the available combos to see which ones the dice result satisfies.

In this design you might define an interface (or simply a function/lambda) that each combo uses to validate a given dice result. One neat design is to create a base structure (or class) for a combo that holds its name and a function that returns true if the result meets the criteria. Then you can store these combo checkers in a container (such as a vector) and simply iterate over them.

2025-03-05 21:59:26: shouldPasteResources: Pasted text: 1. Get Comfortable with Debugging
Debugging is a skill, not just a tool, and C++ can be unforgiving with memory issues, references, and object lifetimes.

✅ Tips:

Learn to use gdb/lldb (command-line) or a GUI debugger like VSCode’s GDB extension or CLion’s debugger.
Use watch variables, step through execution, and inspect memory.
Print less, debug more. Printing std::cout is useful but won’t catch deep memory issues. Debuggers help visualize program flow in ways print statements can’t.
Valgrind (if on Linux/macOS) is great for catching memory leaks and invalid reads/writes.
2. Think in Terms of Memory & Object Lifetime
Since you're working with references, objects, and containers, knowing when and where things are stored is a game-changer.

✅ Tips:

Learn the Rule of 5 (copy constructor, copy assignment, move constructor, move assignment, destructor).
Stack vs Heap: Know when objects are created on the stack vs. heap, and when to prefer one over the other.
RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization): Smart pointers like std::unique_ptr and std::shared_ptr help manage dynamic memory safely.
📌 Example Exercise: Implement a custom smart pointer (like a UniquePtr<T>) to understand how memory management and ownership work internally.

3. Write More Generic & Reusable Code
If you're serious about C++, templates and STL mastery will make your code cleaner, reusable, and scalable.

✅ Tips:

Refactor your existing projects with templated functions and classes instead of repeating logic for different types.
Learn std::function and std::bind for callbacks and higher-order functions.
Use concepts (C++20) to make template constraints easier to understand.
Think in algorithms and iterators:
std::transform (instead of a loop to modify elements)
std::find_if (instead of manually iterating for a condition)
📌 Example Exercise: Write a generic sorting function that works for multiple data types (using templates).

4. Know Your Build System & Compilation Process
Since you’re using CMake, understanding how C++ code is compiled and linked will make debugging easier.

✅ Tips:

Step through the compilation pipeline: preprocessor → compilation → assembling → linking.
Use objdump -t and nm to inspect symbols in compiled object files.
If you’re using CMake, try writing your own minimal build system with Makefiles and clang++/g++.
Use compiler flags to catch issues:
g++ -Wall -Wextra -Werror -fsanitize=address -g myfile.cpp -o myprogram
This enables warnings, errors, and address sanitization for memory errors.
📌 Example Exercise: Manually compile and link a multi-file project without CMake, using just g++ and make.

5. Build Bigger Projects & Organize Code Better
You're already working on a game, which is great. But structuring your project well is a long-term skill that will make everything easier.

✅ Tips:

Follow separation of concerns:
Game loop in main.cpp
Game objects in separate classes
Keep headers clean (use forward declarations where possible)
Try Component-Based Design instead of deep class hierarchies (good for games).
Look into Entity-Component-Systems (ECS) for more modular game development.
📌 Example Exercise: Refactor an existing project to follow SOLID principles (single responsibility, open-closed, etc.).

6. Read & Reverse Engineer High-Quality C++ Code
Reading well-written C++ is just as important as writing it.

✅ Tips:

Read source code from libraries you use (e.g., Raylib, SDL, ImGui).
Study C++ game engines like Godot (C++ bindings) or Doom 3’s source code.
Pick a C++ standard library implementation (like libstdc++) and browse how STL containers like std::vector are implemented.
Contribute to open-source C++ projects on GitHub.
📌 Example Exercise: Pick a function in a library you use, read its implementation, and rewrite a minimal version of it yourself.

7. Master Concurrency & Multithreading
If you want to go beyond basic C++, parallelism and concurrency are key topics.

✅ Tips:

Start with std::thread and learn how to manage race conditions.
Use mutexes (std::mutex) and condition variables (std::condition_variable) properly.
Learn about thread pools to handle many tasks efficiently.
If working on a game, study how game loops handle multi-threading (e.g., physics vs. rendering).
📌 Example Exercise: Write a multi-threaded job system that distributes tasks across multiple CPU cores.

8. Challenge Yourself with Advanced Topics
Since you're aiming for deep mastery, pushing yourself into difficult topics will force you to improve.

✅ Topics to Explore Next:

Modern C++ (C++11 → C++20): Ranges, coroutines, modules.
Custom Memory Allocators: How malloc/free work under the hood.
Metaprogramming: Writing C++ code that generates C++ code at compile-time.
Networking: Using C++ for low-level networking with asio.
Graphics Programming: Vulkan/OpenGL for more control than Raylib.
📌 Example Exercise: Try writing your own lightweight 2D engine from scratch.

data-start="2956" data-end="2965">clang++</code>/<code data-start="2966" data-end="2971">g++</code>.</li><li data-start="2975" data-end="3187">Use<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="2981" data-end="2999">compiler flags</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>to catch issues:<pre class="!overflow-visible" data-start="3021" data-end="3108"><div class="contain-inline-size rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium relative bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary dark:bg-gray-950"><div class="flex items-center text-token-text-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-[5px] h-9 bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary select-none">bash</div><div class="sticky top-9 md:top-[5.75rem]"><div class="absolute bottom-0 right-2 flex h-9 items-center"><div class="flex items-center rounded bg-token-sidebar-surface-primary px-2 font-sans text-xs text-token-text-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center select-none px-4 py-1" aria-label="Copy"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-xs"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M7 5C7 3.34315 8.34315 2 10 2H19C20.6569 2 22 3.34315 22 5V14C22 15.6569 20.6569 17 19 17H17V19C17 20.6569 15.6569 22 14 22H5C3.34315 22 2 20.6569 2 19V10C2 8.34315 3.34315 7 5 7H7V5ZM9 7H14C15.6569 7 17 8.34315 17 10V15H19C19.5523 15 20 14.5523 20 14V5C20 4.44772 19.5523 4 19 4H10C9.44772 4 9 4.44772 9 5V7ZM5 9C4.44772 9 4 9.44772 4 10V19C4 19.5523 4.44772 20 5 20H14C14.5523 20 15 19.5523 15 19V10C15 9.44772 14.5523 9 14 9H5Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy</button></span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex select-none items-center gap-1"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-xs"><path d="M2.5 5.5C4.3 5.2 5.2 4 5.5 2.5C5.8 4 6.7 5.2 8.5 5.5C6.7 5.8 5.8 7 5.5 8.5C5.2 7 4.3 5.8 2.5 5.5Z" fill="currentColor" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path><path d="M5.66282 16.5231L5.18413 19.3952C5.12203 19.7678 5.09098 19.9541 5.14876 20.0888C5.19933 20.2067 5.29328 20.3007 5.41118 20.3512C5.54589 20.409 5.73218 20.378 6.10476 20.3159L8.97693 19.8372C9.72813 19.712 10.1037 19.6494 10.4542 19.521C10.7652 19.407 11.0608 19.2549 11.3343 19.068C11.6425 18.8575 11.9118 18.5882 12.4503 18.0497L20 10.5C21.3807 9.11929 21.3807 6.88071 20 5.5C18.6193 4.11929 16.3807 4.11929 15 5.5L7.45026 13.0497C6.91175 13.5882 6.6425 13.8575 6.43197 14.1657C6.24513 14.4392 6.09299 14.7348 5.97903 stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></svg>Edit</button></span></div></div></div><div class="overflow-y-auto p-4" dir="ltr"><code class="!whitespace-pre language-bash"><span>g++ -Wall -Wextra -Werror -fsanitize=address -g myfile.cpp -o myprogram
</span></code></div></div></pre>This enables warnings, errors, and address sanitization for memory errors.</li></ul><p data-start="3189" data-end="3310" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">📌<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3192" data-end="3213">Example Exercise:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Manually compile and link a multi-file project<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3261" data-end="3278">without CMake</strong>, using just<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="3291" data-end="3296">g++</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="3301" data-end="3307">make</code>.</p><hr data-start="3312" data-end="3315" style="font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><h3 data-start="3317" data-end="3372" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><strong data-start="3321" data-end="3372">5. Build Bigger Projects &amp; Organize Code Better</strong></h3><p data-start="3373" data-end="3521" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">You're already working on a<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3401" data-end="3409">game</strong>, which is great. But structuring your project well is a<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3466" data-end="3485">long-term skill</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>that will make everything easier.</p><p data-start="3523" data-end="3536" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">✅<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3525" data-end="3534">Tips:</strong></p><ul data-start="3537" data-end="3894" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><li data-start="3537" data-end="3723">Follow<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3546" data-end="3572">separation of concerns</strong>:<ul data-start="3578" data-end="3723"><li data-start="3578" data-end="3609"><strong data-start="3580" data-end="3607">Game loop in<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="3595" data-end="3605">main.cpp</code></strong></li><li data-start="3612" data-end="3652"><strong data-start="3614" data-end="3650">Game objects in separate classes</strong></li><li data-start="3655" data-end="3723"><strong data-start="3657" data-end="3721">Keep headers clean (use forward declarations where possible)</strong></li></ul></li><li data-start="3724" data-end="3810">Try<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3730" data-end="3756">Component-Based Design</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>instead of deep class hierarchies (good for games).</li><li data-start="3811" data-end="3894">Look into<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3823" data-end="3857">Entity-Component-Systems (ECS)</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>for more modular game development.</li></ul><p data-start="3896" data-end="4026" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">📌<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3899" data-end="3920">Example Exercise:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Refactor an existing project to follow<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="3960" data-end="3980">SOLID principles</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>(single responsibility, open-closed, etc.).</p><hr data-start="4028" data-end="4031" style="font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><h3 data-start="4033" data-end="4089" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><strong data-start="4037" data-end="4089">6. Read &amp; Reverse Engineer High-Quality C++ Code</strong></h3><p data-start="4090" data-end="4156" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">Reading<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4098" data-end="4118">well-written C++</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>is just as important as writing it.</p><p data-start="4158" data-end="4171" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">✅<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4160" data-end="4169">Tips:</strong></p><ul data-start="4172" data-end="4539" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><li data-start="4172" data-end="4251">Read<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4179" data-end="4194">source code</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>from<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4200" data-end="4221">libraries you use</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>(e.g., Raylib, SDL, ImGui).</li><li data-start="4252" data-end="4341">Study<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4260" data-end="4280">C++ game engines</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>like<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4286" data-end="4310">Godot (C++ bindings)</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>or<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4314" data-end="4338">Doom 3’s source code</strong>.</li><li data-start="4342" data-end="4481">Pick a<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4351" data-end="4390">C++ standard library implementation</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>(like<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="4397" data-end="4408">libstdc++</code>) and browse<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4421" data-end="4478">how STL containers like<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="4447" data-end="4460">std::vector</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>are implemented</strong>.</li><li data-start="4482" data-end="4539">Contribute to<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4498" data-end="4526">open-source C++ projects</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>on GitHub.</li></ul><p data-start="4541" data-end="4684" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">📌<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4544" data-end="4565">Example Exercise:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Pick a function in a library you use,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4604" data-end="4631">read its implementation</strong>, and<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4637" data-end="4666">rewrite a minimal version</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>of it yourself.</p><hr data-start="4686" data-end="4689" style="font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><h3 data-start="4691" data-end="4737" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><strong data-start="4695" data-end="4737">7. Master Concurrency &amp; Multithreading</strong></h3><p data-start="4738" data-end="4823" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">If you want to go beyond basic C++,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4774" data-end="4805">parallelism and concurrency</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>are key topics.</p><p data-start="4825" data-end="4838" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">✅<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4827" data-end="4836">Tips:</strong></p><ul data-start="4839" data-end="5179" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><li data-start="4839" data-end="4910">Start with<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4852" data-end="4867">std::thread</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and learn how to manage race conditions.</li><li data-start="4911" data-end="5007">Use<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="4917" data-end="4995">mutexes (<code data-start="4928" data-end="4940">std::mutex</code>) and condition variables (<code data-start="4967" data-end="4992">std::condition_variable</code>)</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>properly.</li><li data-start="5008" data-end="5074">Learn about<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5022" data-end="5038">thread pools</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>to handle many tasks efficiently.</li><li data-start="5075" data-end="5179">If working on a game,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5099" data-end="5146">study how game loops handle multi-threading</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>(e.g., physics vs. rendering).</li></ul><p data-start="5181" data-end="5295" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">📌<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5184" data-end="5205">Example Exercise:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Write a<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5214" data-end="5243">multi-threaded job system</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>that distributes tasks across multiple CPU cores.</p><hr data-start="5297" data-end="5300" style="font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><h3 data-start="5302" data-end="5352" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><strong data-start="5306" data-end="5352">8. Challenge Yourself with Advanced Topics</strong></h3><p data-start="5353" data-end="5462" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">Since you're aiming for<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5377" data-end="5393">deep mastery</strong>, pushing yourself into difficult topics will force you to improve.</p><p data-start="5464" data-end="5495" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">✅<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5466" data-end="5493">Topics to Explore Next:</strong></p><ul data-start="5496" data-end="5856" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;"><li data-start="5496" data-end="5560"><strong data-start="5498" data-end="5528">Modern C++ (C++11 → C++20)</strong>: Ranges, coroutines, modules.</li><li data-start="5561" data-end="5631"><strong data-start="5563" data-end="5592">Custom Memory Allocators:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>How malloc/free work under the hood.</li><li data-start="5632" data-end="5714"><strong data-start="5634" data-end="5654">Metaprogramming:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Writing C++ code that generates C++ code at compile-time.</li><li data-start="5715" data-end="5782"><strong data-start="5717" data-end="5732">Networking:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Using C++ for low-level networking with<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code data-start="5773" data-end="5779">asio</code>.</li><li data-start="5783" data-end="5856"><strong data-start="5785" data-end="5810">Graphics Programming:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Vulkan/OpenGL for more control than Raylib.</li></ul><p data-start="5858" data-end="5945" style="caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none;">📌<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5861" data-end="5882">Example Exercise:</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>Try writing your own<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong data-start="5904" data-end="5929">lightweight 2D engine</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>from scratch.</p>
